TY  - JOUR
T1  - Adaptive Organizations
AU  - Dessein, Wouter
AU  - Santos, Tano
Y1  - 2006/10/01
PY  - 2006
DA  - 2006/10/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/508031
DO  - 10.1086/508031
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 956
EP  - 995
VL  - 114
IS  - 5
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - We consider organizations that optimally choose the level of adaptation to a changing environment when coordination among specialized tasks is a concern. Adaptive organizations provide employees with flexibility to tailor their tasks to local information. Coordination is maintained by limiting specialization and improving communication. Alternatively, by letting employees stick to some preagreed action plan, organizations can ensure coordination without communication, regardless of the extent of specialization. Among other things, our theory shows how extensive specialization results in organizations that ignore local knowledge, and it explains why improvements in communication technology may reduce specialization by pushing organizations to become more adaptive.
AB  - We consider organizations that optimally choose the level of adaptation to a changing environment when coordination among specialized tasks is a concern. Adaptive organizations provide employees with flexibility to tailor their tasks to local information. Coordination is maintained by limiting specialization and improving communication. Alternatively, by letting employees stick to some preagreed action plan, organizations can ensure coordination without communication, regardless of the extent of specialization. Among other things, our theory shows how extensive specialization results in organizations that ignore local knowledge, and it explains why improvements in communication technology may reduce specialization by pushing organizations to become more adaptive.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/508031
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/508031
Y2  - 2024/03/19
